 by its stylistic verve and intellectual scope. Drawing on expertise from a range of scholars, this volume examines Daniel’s capacious works and demonstrates their significance to many scholarly conversations, including the history of late medieval medicine. It explains the background for Daniel’s uroscopic and herbal work, describes all known versions of the Liber Uricrisiarum and traces revisions over time, analyses Daniel’s representations of his own medical practice, and demonstrates his influence on later medical and literary writers. Both a companion to the recently published reading edition of the Liber Uricrisiarum and a work of original scholarship in its own right, this collection promotes a wider understanding of Daniel’s texts and prompts new discoveries about their importance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 0aMedical literaturezEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMedical writingxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMedicine, MedievalzEngland. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aHenry Daniel.  aLiber Uricrisiarum.  abook history.  ahistory of medicine.  amedieval English vernacularity.  amedieval herbs.  amedieval medicine.  amedieval poetics and narrative.  amedieval uroscopy.1 aBlack, Winston, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBower, Hannah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarvey, E. Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Peter Murray, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStar, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStar, Sarah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTavormina, M. Teresa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWallis, Faith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.g